      </aside>
    </header>
    <div class="body">
      <div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26379457#p26379457" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26379429#p26379429" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">Astramancer</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><div class="quotetitle"><a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/viewtopic.php?p=26379417#p26379417" class="postlink" rel="nofollow">jxmzsr</a> wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">Someone tell us again how secure bitcoin is.</div><br /><br />So far, pretty secure.  You'll notice how hackers have to compromise the exchanges.  They're not compromising the protocol.</div><br /><br />protocol doesn't do much good if they can make off with bitcoins in the first place.</div><br /><br />You're right.  We should stop using banks because they sometimes get robbed.  We should stop using wallets because they sometimes get pickpocketed.<br /><br />Heck, we should stop using cash because someone could just rip it right out of your hand!<br /><br />Which is to say, Bitcoin is specifically a method of having unique data that you can securely send from one address to another in such a way that the sender (nor anyone else, really) can not revoke or change the transaction.  No compromises (that we know of) have broken the fundamental underpinnings of Bitcoin.  They've broken poor security around access to the unique data.<br /><br />So far, the only theoretical method I've heard of with regards to defeating to protocol itself, rather than individuals using the protocol, is the 51% attack where someone controls enough of the mining to send lies which are accepted as truth to the blockchain.
      
        <p class="edited">Last edited by <a href="http://arstechnica.com/civis/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=344279&amp;sid=4630d63c1d39d426d6a5063cb6de6ff9">Astramancer</a> on Thu Mar 06, 2014 12:05 pm</p>
      
